        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1151034466" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3734791232389874778"><i>Original one line summary review - March 2015:</i><br/><br/>A poised, elliptical story of post-war Japan and contrasting cultures, generations and family relationships.<br/><br/><i>Further reflections after re-reading and face to face discussion with the Five Leaves book group - Nov 2019:</i><br/>When this book was chosen for this month&apos;s Five Leaves book group discussion, I was initially a little reluctant to participate, having read and quite enjoyed the book four years ago I remembered very little about it, and would not have p</span>
  <span id="freeText3734791232389874778" style="display:none"><i>Original one line summary review - March 2015:</i><br /><br />A poised, elliptical story of post-war Japan and contrasting cultures, generations and family relationships.<br /><br /><i>Further reflections after re-reading and face to face discussion with the Five Leaves book group - Nov 2019:</i><br />When this book was chosen for this month's Five Leaves book group discussion, I was initially a little reluctant to participate, having read and quite enjoyed the book four years ago I remembered very little about it, and would not have put it anywhere near the top of my list of books I must re-read. As it turned out, I am very glad I did, as the deliberate ambiguity made it a very interesting choice for a discussion that opened up a wide variety of perspectives and interpretations, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[in particular the idea that Sachiko and Mariko are imaginary versions of Etsuko and Keiko that embody aspects of their past that Etsuko would rather forget <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. In my own second reading I was much more aware of the political overtones of the story, and I now understand Ishiguro's slightly tongue-in-cheek comment that his first three novels were essentially the same story rather better.</span>
