        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2972347759" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17210944989040441116"><u>#1 for Ishiguro challenge</u><br/><br/>This is the third book from Ishiguro I&apos;ve read, and I am a little perplexed. Three were quite different from one another. <br/><br/>First I read <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6334.Never_Let_Me_Go' title='Never Let Me Go by Kazuo Ishiguro' rel='nofollow noopener'>Never Let Me Go</a>. Though I read it a while ago, I don&apos;t remember the book that well, so a re-read is needed. But I can say that I am not quite fond of dystopia and didn&apos;t have a special connection with the book.<br/><br/>The second was <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28921.The_Remains_of_the_Day' title='The Remains of the Day by Kazuo Ishiguro' rel='nofollow noopener'>The Remains of the Day</a>. I was impressed, more than impressed. I love both Japanese and British culture, literature,</span>
  <span id="freeText17210944989040441116" style="display:none"><u>#1 for Ishiguro challenge</u><br /><br />This is the third book from Ishiguro I've read, and I am a little perplexed. Three were quite different from one another. <br /><br />First I read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6334.Never_Let_Me_Go" title="Never Let Me Go by Kazuo Ishiguro" rel="nofollow noopener">Never Let Me Go</a>. Though I read it a while ago, I don't remember the book that well, so a re-read is needed. But I can say that I am not quite fond of dystopia and didn't have a special connection with the book.<br /><br />The second was <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/28921.The_Remains_of_the_Day" title="The Remains of the Day by Kazuo Ishiguro" rel="nofollow noopener">The Remains of the Day</a>. I was impressed, more than impressed. I love both Japanese and British culture, literature, and melancholy, so imagine my feelings for this one. This book made me order every possible writing by Ishiguro I could find and start from the beginning. <br /><br />The beginning was this. Ishiguro was trying to find his identity. It's mixture of Japanese literature influenced by Russian classics. Though he went with a different direction, it feels like Murakami and Ishiguro started from the same starting point - Dostoevsky. But I am very happy for where he ended up.<br />I loved the mood of the book. Though, this was his debut and was row compared to his other writings, I was reading about 5 pages every day trying to slowly enjoy this delicious piece of literature. I was in heaven.<br />I still need at least 3 people who read this book and have different points of view to discuss this book!<br />And maybe I need a re-read.<br /><br />P.S. excellent book for book clubs. You are going to discuss this for about 3-4 hours 🤔</span>
