    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3715038022" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3715038022" />
    <a title="Paul" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/30751659-paul"><img alt="Paul" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1525336320p2/30751659.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3715038022?book_show_action=true">Dec 28, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paul" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paul" href="/user/show/30751659-paul">Paul</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780571245659" href="/book/show/6336063-a-pale-view-of-hills">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3715038022" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11409985525517541765">I&apos;ve been meaning to read this short novel for years. The final prompt was the passionate advocacy of my writer friend, Jess. Some forty years after Ishiguro&apos;s time at my alma mater resulted in this novel, I&apos;ve finally got around to it. Meanwhile Ishiguro is approaching old age. It&apos;s a strange life, isn&apos;t it? <br/><br/>There&apos;s a pleasure to be had from some writers&apos; oeuvres, charting the development of their craft, either in real time or retrospectively. The early efforts typically lack the style and acco</span>
  <span id="freeText11409985525517541765" style="display:none">I've been meaning to read this short novel for years. The final prompt was the passionate advocacy of my writer friend, Jess. Some forty years after Ishiguro's time at my alma mater resulted in this novel, I've finally got around to it. Meanwhile Ishiguro is approaching old age. It's a strange life, isn't it? <br /><br />There's a pleasure to be had from some writers' oeuvres, charting the development of their craft, either in real time or retrospectively. The early efforts typically lack the style and accomplishment of the mature works. I recently read <i>Campo Santo</i> by W G Sebald, the essays in which are arranged chronologically. That mesmeric master was definitely a late developer. Other writers apparently arrive fully formed. Such seems to be the case with Kazuo Ishiguro. Apparently, his facility for dialogue and description materialised ready-made. <br /><br />The style and concerns have much in common with Ishiguro's second novel, <i>An Artist of the Floating World</i>. Both have Japanese settings (for the most part) and investigate the tensions in that society in the aftermath of war, most especially the pull between tradition and the new ways and ideas. Both feature old men who supported Japan's disastrous militaristic regime being confronted with their past by a new generation. In this case, it's Ogata, retired headteacher and father-in-law to the protagonist Etsuko. Ishiguro is adept at social critique without overt criticism, allowing characters' actions to speak for themselves. Etsuko's husband, Jiro, is a chip off the old block, as they say, and treats her dismissively. She must choose whether to remain in this stultifying environment or to seek the greater freedom she'll find as a woman in the West. There's a minor problem, though; she's already pregnant with their first child. The novel is narrated by Etsuko, now an older woman, living in England. <br /><br /><i>A Pale View of Hills</i> actually has much in common with the last novel I read, <i>The Cemetery in Barnes</i> by Gabriel Josipovici. There's more than a whiff of 'unreliable' narration in each of them. In the latter, two women seem to morph into one towards the end of the novel. Exactly the same thing happens in the former, where Etsuko's experience appears to conflate with that of her 'friend', Sachiko, whose tale she is supposedly relating. In a key section, which seems to repeat a scene from the start of the novel, it becomes unclear whether Etsuko is talking to her own daughter or her friend's. There's a framing device a-la-<i>Heart of Darkness</i>, the relevance of which only becomes apparent at the end. Etsuko is talking to her daughter, Niki, about a day she spent with her friend in the mountains outside Nagasaki. It's an episode related in some detail, earlier in the book. She refers to Niki's older sister, Keiko:<br /><br /><i>'Oh, there was nothing special about it. I was just remembering it, that's all. Keiko was happy that day. We rode on the cable-cars.' I gave a laugh and turned to Niki. 'No, there was nothing special about. It was just a happy memory, that's all.'</i> <br /><br />But Keiko hadn't been born yet and that day out had been all about Sachiko's daughter, Mariko instead... Incidentally, this revelation appears on the penultimate page of the novel, just as the key moment does in Josipovici's book. Is Etsuko using Sachiko's experiences to explain her own story to herself? Or is she projecting emotions on to her unborn child? It's inconclusive, of course. <br /><br />One unusual characteristic is how adeptly Ishiguro manages to narrate through the voice of a woman. My benchmark for this act of literary ventriloquism is <i>A Clergyman's Daughter</i>. In the great miserabilist's weakest novel, 'Dorothy' is quite clearly Orwell in a maiden aunt's wig. There's not a hint of that here. A further aspect; it's not for the cat-obsessed. This makes the third novel I've read with a Japanese setting that features cat abuse. Unspeakable things also happen to a cat in Mishima's <i>The Sailor Who Fell from Grace with the Sea</i> and in Murakami's execrable <i>Kafka on the Shore</i> (the most annoying aspect of which is that it besmirches the name of a genuine literary genius by association). If I were a cat, I'd not be making plans to visit Japan anytime soon. <br /><br />Does this first novel demonstrate that it was always his destiny to achieve Nobel Prize glory? In the (slightly adjusted) words of the great poet, M Bolan; 'Ishiguro, is it you?' Those familiar with his works will know the refrain. 'Yeah, yeah, yeah...'</span>
  <a data-text-id="11409985525517541765" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


