  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3276696574" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3276696574" />
    <a title="Asma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/97354050-asma"><img alt="Asma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1642181794p2/97354050.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3276696574?book_show_action=true">Jul 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Asma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Asma" href="/user/show/97354050-asma">Asma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/97354050-asma?shelf=century-20th">century-20th</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/97354050-asma?shelf=2020">2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/97354050-asma?shelf=nobel">nobel</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3276696574" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14656665827241465122">Ishiguro&apos;s excellent debut,<i> A pale view of hills</i>, is told through the perspective of a Japanese woman Etsuko, now living in England dwelling on the recent suicide of her older daughter, Keiko. <br/>The story alternates between her past life in Japan and and present life in English countryside. She reflects on a particular hot summer in Nagasaki when she befriends her neighbor, Sachiko.<br/><br/>The whole story is told in the form of dialogue. As Etusko reminiscences, her memory has become hazy with the passage</span>
  <span id="freeText14656665827241465122" style="display:none">Ishiguro's excellent debut,<i> A pale view of hills</i>, is told through the perspective of a Japanese woman Etsuko, now living in England dwelling on the recent suicide of her older daughter, Keiko. <br />The story alternates between her past life in Japan and and present life in English countryside. She reflects on a particular hot summer in Nagasaki when she befriends her neighbor, Sachiko.<br /><br />The whole story is told in the form of dialogue. As Etusko reminiscences, her memory has become hazy with the passage of time. She relieves her memories but seems to believe :<i> There's nothing to be gained in going over such matters again.</i><br /><br /> We are not sure if the things were "actually" so as she recalls them or whether she is really telling the truth? The intentions of the characters are not always clear. In a lot of instances, they repeat their dialogue (which can be awkward and frustrating ).A lot of things remain vague or untold.<br /><br />As Ishiguro said once:<br /><br /><i>As a writer, I'm more interested in what people tell themselves happened rather than what actually happened.</i><br /><br />That basically sums up the narrative voice in this book. <br /><br />Ishiguro's prose is simple, meticulous, serene and beautiful; no frills and flowers. The novel is just under 200 pages, language easy to read; still it demands for rather slow and careful reading.<br />Characters have a very formal and polite way of talking. You'll see a lot of these kind of phrases;<br />"I suppose so."<br />"Why, thank you."<br />"Why, how kind of you."<br />"How inconsiderate of me."<br /><br />There's nostalgia and a constant underlying feeling of melancholy and guilt runs throughout the novel. Etsuko somewhat deems herself responsible for her daughter's suicide. Apparently, nothing significant happens in the book. There's a lot of mystery and enigma. We don't know what became of certain characters. <br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ In chapter 10, there's a brief episode of shifting of pronouns, which creates confusion and raises questions. Whether Sachiko and Etsuko , and Mariko and Keiko are the same person? If yes, then we get explanation why Keiko commited suicide. If no, we don't really know why Etsuko left Japan and ended up in England. What happened in her past life; there's no clear explanation. Was Etsuko really innocent? <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />This novel is quite an interesting reflection on family dynamics, dislocation, and unreliability of memory. There's "nothing much" yet "so much" in this novel. <br />Interesting to see the post-war Japan; the change of government system into democratic one, and reorganization of educational system. We get to know some about Japanese culture; which I very much liked; gave me a familiar feeling and recognition of "East".<br /><br />The's some clash between "old Japanese ways" vs new 'American inspired' ways. The older generation ( Ogata, Etsuko's father-in-law) doesn't approve of new systems:<br /><br /><i>"Discipline, loyalty, such things held japan together once. That may sound fanciful, but it's true. people were bound by a sense duty. Towards one's family, towards superiors, towards the country. But now instead, there's all talk of democracy. You hear it whenever people want to be selfish, whenever they want to forget obligations."</i><br /><br />Whereas, the younger generation has different mindset:<br /><br /><i>"In your day, children in Japan were taught terrible things. They were taught lies of most damaging kind. Worst of all, they were taught not see, not to question. And that’s why the country was plunged into the most evil disaster in the entire history".</i><br /><br />We see how circumstances of people changed by war: people losing their families; coping with new situations; wealthy women working in noodle shops. But then, there is glimmer of hope in the form of Mrs. Fujiwara.<br /><i> Looking back on the past or looking forward to the future?</i><br />This book is going to ask you a lot of questions and leave you pondering over the fates of characters. It had me thinking over the significance of the title. A lot of things are left for the reader to decide, which can be frustrating for those especially who like things to get "resolved".<br /><br />Quite an <i>ordinarily extraordinary</i> novel!</span>
  <a data-text-id="14656665827241465122" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

