    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1922831141" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1922831141" />
    <a title="Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35482263-gumble-s-yard---golden-reviewer"><img alt="Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607273231p2/35482263.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1922831141?book_show_action=true">Feb 23, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer" href="/user/show/35482263-gumble-s-yard---golden-reviewer">Gumble&#39;s Yard - Golden Reviewer</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35482263-gumble-s-yard---golden-reviewer?shelf=2009">2009</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1922831141" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9184188172230543320">Haunting and enigmatic tale – clearly a talented writer if for this book (his first book after a creative writing course) a little too clever<br/><br/>I was engrossed while reading it and read it too fast; meaning to go back and resolve any remaining contradictions after the author had presumably unravelled most of them. Then I was shocked when the book seemed to end mid-story – to the extent I was genuinely shocked to turn over to a blank page. After reflection and reading some literary criticisms and au</span>
  <span id="freeText9184188172230543320" style="display:none">Haunting and enigmatic tale – clearly a talented writer if for this book (his first book after a creative writing course) a little too clever<br /><br />I was engrossed while reading it and read it too fast; meaning to go back and resolve any remaining contradictions after the author had presumably unravelled most of them. Then I was shocked when the book seemed to end mid-story – to the extent I was genuinely shocked to turn over to a blank page. After reflection and reading some literary criticisms and author interviews I appreciated the deliberate ambiguity and enjoyed reflecting on the themes and ideas in the book. <br /><br />After their first meeting Mariko identifies Etsuko as the mysterious woman across the river – something which is shrugged off. At a crucial point late in her story when trying to talk to Mariko about not being worried about going off with Frank Etsuko suddenly shifts from you to we – initially this seems a mistake or an attempt at reassurance. In both episodes Mariko is terrified by a rope Etsuko is holding and which Etsuko says simply caught around her foot. All of these add an element of blending and uncertainty to Etsuko’s life, reminiscences and dreams (of a girl swinging on a rope). <br /><br />My view is that the author fascinated by people who in telling other people’s stories as a proxy for their own “I have a friend who ...”) wanted to explore the possibility of someone who used the same device in their own thoughts as a way of coping with the horrors they had lived through and trying to examine and justify the choices they had made. This is combined with the Japanese trying themselves to come to terms with their militarist past. The role of women in Japan compared to US/UK and the responsibilities of motherhood are other themes. An overarching theme is coming to terms with loss and horror and moving on – Keiko, some implicit terrible ending to the Mariko story and beneath everything the devastation and personal loss in Nagasaki</span>
  <a data-text-id="9184188172230543320" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


